Let’s talk about what’s going on in wine country at this time of year 🍷
It’s winter time in Sonoma county - and this year has been extra cold ❄️I’ve been so freezing - so the vines are dormant for now. At this time pruning will start, or has already been completed at most wineries. 
✂️This is one of the most expensive and most important activities in the vineyard. Pruning makes way for fruit to grow efficiently, not pruning creates too much foliage which limits the plant’s ability to set fruit buds for the following year. 🍇
And no one wants that
There’s also a lot of bottling happening at wineries right now, getting last years wines ready to go to the customers or sit for a few years before selling. 🍾
This happens to be my favorite time in wine country. What’s your favorite time? 
.
.
.
#wine #winery #vineyards #winecountry #sonomacounty #sonoma #winelover #wineeducation #youcansipwithus

Take a trip with me to @deloachvineyards 🍷🍇☀️
Recently got to try out their new Seasons in the Vineyard winegrower lunch and tour!
Started off the tour with a glass of their lovely Marin county chardonnay and off we went on a very educational tour of their organic vineyard! Sophie was so sweet and gave a great tour, showed off their gardens and mini farm with sheep and chickens! We even got some eggs fresh on the tour. 
After the tour, i had a great lunch from @oakvillegrocery and the rest of the tasting, with two Pinots and a Zinfandel. Their Pennachio vineyard Pinot Noir was to die for!
Highly recommend booking this on your next visit to Sonoma county! The dates are Saturday May 20th and Saturday August 12!
Book yours on their website now!

As a millennial, I very much enjoyed the name of this red blend from @thevicewine 
This is a fantastic wine that any millennial would love to sip on. Blackberries, vanilla and blueberries on the nose. Black cherry, coffee and fig on the palate. This won me over with the blend - 63% petite sirah (I LOVE petite sirah) 21% Malbec, 8% Primitivo, 7% Tempranillo and 1% Charbono. 
If you haven’t heard of the Vice Wines - The Vice Wine is a Napa Valley luxury wine brand that makes wine in small batches. Each batch is crafted from single grape varietals sourced from hand selected vineyards that best express the grape varietal and the region that it comes from. 
I can’t wait to try more wine from them in the future! 
.

So let’s go friends! Go book your visit today!

It’s always a good time at a party for @sutrowine 
Alice Sutro is honestly the coolest winemaker and owner around. Founded by Alice Warnecke Sutro in 2012, they source grapes exclusively farmed by Alice’s family at Warnecke Ranch and Vineyard located on Chalk Hill Road in Alexander Valley, Sonoma County. Alice is the first in her family to produce vineyard designated estate wines from this unique terroir. They produce 1200 cases of Bordeaux varietals. Merlot, Cabernet Sauvignon, Sauvignon Blanc and a great rose make up their bottles and they are all so tasty. Their merlot is one of my favorites! 
If you are interested in trying her wines, you can go to her website to purchase or if you are in the area you can book a hike and a tasting with Alice herself!

Celebrating my first Mother’s Day with @paulakornellsparkling 🍾
So excited to be celebrating my first Mother’s Day this year and it’s a great excuse to open some sparkling wine! 
Paula Kornell Sparkling wines is made in Napa Valley and Paula herself hails from a very wine heavy family. Her family owned Hanns kornell champagne cellars, one of the first to use méthode champenoise in california. 
Paula Kornell wines are made to be food friendly and enjoyed with family - so a perfect bottle to celebrate with! With notes of honeysuckle, peaches and toast, and only $22.00 a bottle, it’s a winner for me! 
So cheers to all the mothers out there and hope you choose to open a bottle of Paula Kornell California Brut on Sunday! 🍾

‼️ big announcement folks!
Today starts my new project - showing 100 fun things to do all over Sonoma county! And instead of just writing a list, I’m going to do all of them because I am crazy. 
I wanted to start showing what fun and cool things Sonoma County has to offer, child friendly AND not child friendly. I’ll still be wine tasting and reviewing wine in between this series don’t you worry my friends, wine content isn’t going away. I just wanted to include doing things with my son as well 😊
I don’t know how long this series will take, but I can’t wait to take you along for the ride!
Activity one will be posted tomorrow! 
Any suggestions on where I should check out next? Please share your ideas!

1/100 Fun things to do in Sonoma County
Howarth Park in Santa Rosa
I’ve been here one time to take photos and that was it, never knew there was a train ride, merry go round and petting barn! 
Howarth Park is huge - so many different play structures, a lake to fish, kayaking with great walking trails. 
Obviously very child friendly and you can bring your dog if they are leashed up!
Jeffy was super uninterested the entire time but he’s a hard baby to please. I can’t wait to come back when he’s older! 
$2 a person to ride the train or merry go round, kids under 12 months are free to ride 
Where do you want us to check out next?

Since it’s the first day of summer, figured my activity 2/100 of fun things to do in Sonoma County would be getting ice cream!
So many fun places to check out with magical ice cream at every spot. My go to, and only 10 minutes from my house is @screaminmimisicecream 
Scott even took me here on one of our first dates almost ten years ago! I’ve loved it ever since. Great place to bring your entire family
My other favorites in Sonoma County are @noblefolk @nimbleandfinns @angelas_icecream @twodognightcreamery and wicked slush! 
What’s your go to ice cream spot? 🍦

3/100 - Wednesday Night Market in Santa Rosa CA
Absolutely family friendly of all kinds - Jeffy at 4 months had a blast 
Many different food, drink, activity options with live music! Perfect way to spend a summer night and a good way to break up the week! 
Have you been to Wednesday Night Market?

Let’s talk about ✨SPARKLING ✨ 🍾
Not all sparkling wine is the same. There are many different kinds of sparkling wine from different regions of the world. Here are three main ones you’ll see at your local stores and what the difference is:

🍾CHAMPAGNE - champagne is called champagne only if it’s from the Champagne region of France. Good ole champagne is going to have toasty flavor notes because of the extra aging on the lees (also known as yeast). You are going to find that the bubbles are smaller and the three main grapes used to make Champagne is Chardonnay, Pinot Noir and Pinot Meunier. Champagne is usually going to be the most expensive which is why a lot of people save this for special occasions. 

🍾PROSECCO - Prosecco comes from the Veneto region in northeast Italy, and is only made from the Glera grape. Unlike champagne, you are going to find more green apple and citrus notes. It’s also going to be a lot cheaper than Champagne as it’s cheaper to make, but that does NOT mean it’s worse because it’s cheaper. The bubbles are also bigger than champagne. 

🍾CAVA - Cava originates from Spain and similar to Champagne in terms of flavor. It is on the cheaper side like Prosecco. It’s typically made from three grape varietals - Macabeu, Parellada and Xarello and comes in four classifications based on sugar content. This is my personal favorite of the sparkling!

Along with it being spooky season, October is Merlot Month! #merlotme 
Everywhere, people are celebrating Merlot in all sorts of ways, as merlot is one of the worlds most planted wine varietal. 
Merlot is French for “the little blackbird” and is a very adaptable grape to many different climates. Merlot is a dry wine, medium to full bodied wine with moderate acidity. It has many ranges of flavors - from graphite to blackberries to cocoa to vanilla. 
After the movie Sideways came out in 2004, Merlot took a giant beating as people stopped drinking it just because Paul Giamattis character decided to be dramatic and says he hated merlot. Honestly impressive that one line in one movie had that big of an effect on the industry. 
However, Merlot is making its way back into peoples hearts, and I for one have always loved a good bottle of one. In fact a Merlot was the varietal of the bottle that got me obsessed with wine in the first place. 
But open a Merlot this month! You won’t be disappointed. (This @benzigerwinery one was a great way to kick of the month)
